# Glossary: A–D

## A

**Activated carbon**  
A highly porous carbon material used to adsorb dissolved organic compounds, taste-and-odor compounds, and some PFAS. It may be used as powdered activated carbon (PAC) or granular activated carbon (GAC).

**Adsorption**  
The attachment of molecules from water onto the surface of a solid material such as activated carbon or biochar. Adsorption differs from absorption, in which a substance enters the interior of another material.

**Advanced oxidation process (AOP)**  
A treatment process that creates highly reactive chemical species, commonly hydroxyl radicals, to destroy organic contaminants. UV light combined with hydrogen peroxide is a common AOP.

**Advanced Water Purification (AWP)**  
A term used in Arizona and elsewhere for highly treated recycled water that is purified for potable use. On this website, AWP and AWT overlap, although AWP often refers specifically to potable-reuse treatment.

**Advanced Water Treatment (AWT)**  
A multi-barrier treatment approach that goes beyond conventional wastewater treatment to remove pathogens, trace organic chemicals, salts where necessary, and other contaminants. AWT may support potable reuse or higher-quality environmental discharge.

**Aeration**  
The transfer of air or oxygen into water or wastewater. In biological wastewater treatment, aeration supplies oxygen to microorganisms and is often one of the largest energy uses at a treatment plant.

**Aquifer**  
A body of permeable rock or sediment that stores and transmits groundwater.

**Aquifer recharge**  
The addition of water to an aquifer, either naturally through infiltration or intentionally through recharge basins or injection wells.

**Aquifer storage and recovery (ASR)**  
The intentional injection or recharge of water into an aquifer for later recovery through wells.

**Arizona Department of Environmental Quality (ADEQ)**  
The Arizona agency responsible for environmental regulation, including drinking water, wastewater, reclaimed water, and advanced water purification permitting.

**Arizona Department of Water Resources (ADWR)**  
The Arizona agency responsible for water-resource management, groundwater regulation, and water-supply planning.

**Arizona Water Infrastructure Finance Authority (WIFA)**  
A state financing organization that administers loans and grants for water, wastewater, conservation, and related infrastructure.

## B

**Bacteria**  
Microscopic organisms. Some are beneficial and are essential to biological wastewater treatment; others can cause disease.

**Bardenpho process**  
A multi-stage biological wastewater-treatment process designed to remove nitrogen, and in some configurations phosphorus, by alternating anoxic and aerobic conditions.

**Beneficial reuse**  
The planned use of reclaimed water or biosolids for a useful purpose rather than disposal.

**Biochar**  
A carbon-rich material produced by heating biomass in low-oxygen conditions. Depending on feedstock and processing, biochar may be used for soil applications, adsorption, or environmental treatment.

**Biological activated carbon (BAC)**  
Activated carbon media that supports both adsorption and biological degradation. Ozone is often used upstream to make organic compounds more biodegradable.

**Biochemical oxygen demand (BOD)**  
A measure of the oxygen microorganisms consume while degrading biodegradable material in water. It is a standard measure of wastewater strength.

**Biosolids**  
Treated sewage sludge that meets regulatory requirements for disposal or beneficial use.

**Brackish water**  
Water with more dissolved salts than typical fresh water but less than seawater.

**Brine**  
A concentrated salt solution. Reverse osmosis produces a brine or concentrate stream containing the salts and contaminants rejected by the membrane.

## C

**C-aquifer**  
The regional Coconino Aquifer, an important groundwater source for Flagstaff and other northern Arizona communities.

**Chemicals of emerging concern (CECs)**  
A broad group of chemicals detected in water that may not yet have comprehensive regulatory standards. Examples include pharmaceuticals, hormones, personal-care-product ingredients, and industrial compounds.

**Chlorination**  
The application of chlorine or chlorine compounds for disinfection and residual protection in a water-distribution system.

**Class A+ reclaimed water**  
Arizona’s highest reclaimed-water class, produced through treatment and disinfection requirements suitable for many non-potable uses. It is not the same as purified drinking water.

**Climate resilience**  
The ability of a water system to continue functioning under drought, wildfire, extreme precipitation, changing temperatures, and other climate-related stresses.

**Coagulation**  
The addition of chemicals that destabilize fine suspended particles so they can combine into larger particles for removal.

**Concentrate**  
The reject stream from a membrane process such as reverse osmosis. It contains elevated concentrations of salts and other rejected constituents.

**Contaminant**  
A physical, chemical, biological, or radiological substance present in water. Presence alone does not necessarily mean a health standard is exceeded.

**Contaminant of emerging concern**  
See **Chemicals of emerging concern (CECs)**.

**Conventional wastewater treatment**  
Treatment typically including screening, solids removal, biological treatment, clarification, and disinfection. It is primarily designed for solids, biodegradable organics, nutrients, and pathogens—not complete removal of all trace chemicals.

**Cryptosporidium**  
A chlorine-resistant protozoan pathogen that can cause gastrointestinal illness. Potable-reuse treatment trains must provide validated barriers against it.

## D

**Desalination**  
The removal of dissolved salts from water, most commonly by reverse osmosis.

**Direct potable reuse (DPR)**  
The introduction of highly purified recycled water into a drinking-water treatment or distribution system without an environmental buffer such as an aquifer or reservoir. Arizona now commonly uses the term Advanced Water Purification.

**Disinfection**  
Treatment intended to inactivate disease-causing microorganisms. Common methods include chlorine, ultraviolet light, and ozone.

**Disinfection byproducts (DBPs)**  
Compounds formed when disinfectants react with natural organic matter or other constituents in water.

**Dissolved organic carbon (DOC)**  
The portion of organic carbon that passes through a specified filter. DOC can affect treatment performance, disinfection byproduct formation, and adsorption demand.

**Dissolved solids**  
Minerals, salts, metals, and other substances dissolved in water. Total dissolved solids (TDS) is the most common aggregate measure.

**Drought resilience**  
The ability of a water system to maintain service during prolonged dry conditions or reduced surface-water availability.

