# Glossary: M–R

## M

**Membrane bioreactor (MBR)**  
A wastewater process combining biological treatment with membrane filtration, producing very low suspended solids and a high-quality effluent.

**Membrane filtration**  
Separation using a thin barrier with controlled pore size or molecular selectivity. Microfiltration, ultrafiltration, nanofiltration, and reverse osmosis are membrane processes.

**Microfiltration (MF)**  
A low-pressure membrane process that removes suspended particles and many microorganisms but does not remove most dissolved salts or small organic molecules.

**Microorganism**  
A microscopic living organism, including bacteria, protozoa, and fungi. Viruses are generally discussed with microorganisms even though they are not cellular organisms.

**Micropollutant**  
A contaminant present at very low concentration, often micrograms or nanograms per liter, that may still have biological or treatment significance.

**Monitoring surrogate**  
A continuously or rapidly measured parameter used to indicate whether a treatment process is functioning as intended when direct measurement of every contaminant is impractical.

**Multi-barrier treatment**  
A treatment philosophy using several independent or complementary processes so that failure of one barrier does not result in loss of public-health protection.

## N

**Nanofiltration (NF)**  
A pressure-driven membrane process with removal characteristics between ultrafiltration and reverse osmosis. It can remove hardness and many larger dissolved molecules while allowing more salts to pass than RO.

**Nano-zero-valent iron (nZVI)**  
Very small particles of elemental iron used for chemical reduction and contaminant treatment. nZVI can be combined with biochar to improve handling and provide multiple removal mechanisms.

**National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System (NPDES)**  
The federal Clean Water Act permitting program for discharges to surface waters. Arizona administers its counterpart as AZPDES.

**Natural organic matter (NOM)**  
Organic material naturally present in source water. It can affect color, taste, adsorption, oxidation demand, and disinfection byproduct formation.

**Nitrate**  
An oxidized form of nitrogen. It is a regulated drinking-water contaminant and an important nutrient in wastewater and environmental waters.

**Nitrogen removal**  
Treatment that converts or removes ammonia, nitrate, and other nitrogen forms, commonly through nitrification and denitrification.

## O

**Online monitoring**  
Continuous or frequent automated measurement of treatment performance, such as turbidity, conductivity, total organic carbon, UV intensity, or membrane integrity.

**Organic contaminant**  
A carbon-containing chemical compound in water. The category includes natural organic matter and synthetic compounds such as solvents, pesticides, pharmaceuticals, and PFAS precursors.

**Osmosis**  
The natural movement of water across a semipermeable membrane from a lower-solute solution toward a higher-solute solution.

**Ozone**  
A powerful oxidant used for disinfection, taste-and-odor control, and destruction or transformation of many organic contaminants.

## P

**Pathogen**  
A disease-causing microorganism or infectious agent, including viruses, bacteria, protozoa, and parasites.

**Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS)**  
A large family of highly persistent fluorinated chemicals used in many industrial and consumer products. Some PFAS are regulated in drinking water and can be difficult to remove.

**Pharmaceuticals and personal care products (PPCPs)**  
Medicines, fragrances, cosmetics ingredients, and related substances that may enter wastewater through use and disposal.

**Pilot study**  
A small-scale or demonstration-scale test used to evaluate treatment performance under local conditions before full-scale design.

**Potable reuse**  
The intentional use of highly treated recycled water as a drinking-water supply.

**Powdered activated carbon (PAC)**  
Finely divided activated carbon added directly to water for adsorption and later removed with solids.

**Pretreatment**  
Treatment applied before a main process to protect equipment, improve performance, or reduce contaminants.

**Primary treatment**  
The physical removal of settleable and floatable solids from wastewater, commonly using sedimentation.

**Protozoa**  
Single-celled organisms. Some, including Giardia and Cryptosporidium, are waterborne pathogens.

**Public acceptance**  
The degree to which residents and stakeholders understand, trust, and support a water project.

**Purified water**  
Recycled water that has undergone advanced treatment to meet specified potable-reuse requirements. It is not necessarily the same as finished drinking water until all regulatory and distribution requirements are met.

## Q

**Quality assurance/quality control (QA/QC)**  
Procedures used to ensure that sampling, laboratory analysis, monitoring, and reporting are accurate and reliable.

## R

**Reclaimed water**  
Wastewater that has been treated for beneficial non-potable use. Reclaimed water quality varies by treatment class and intended use.

**Recharge basin**  
A surface basin designed to infiltrate water into an aquifer.

**Recovery rate**  
The percentage of feed water converted to product water by a membrane or treatment process. The remainder becomes reject or concentrate.

**Red Gap Ranch (RGR)**  
City-owned property east of Flagstaff being evaluated as a future groundwater source requiring wells, treatment, pumping, and a long transmission pipeline.

**Redundancy**  
Backup capacity or alternate equipment and supplies that allow service to continue when part of a system is unavailable.

**Regulatory framework**  
The laws, rules, permits, guidance, and agency procedures governing a project.

**Residuals**  
Solid or liquid waste streams generated by treatment, including sludge, spent media, membrane concentrate, and backwash water.

**Reverse osmosis (RO)**  
A high-pressure membrane process that removes most dissolved salts and many organic contaminants. RO produces purified water and a concentrate stream requiring management.

**Risk assessment**  
A systematic evaluation of the likelihood and consequences of adverse outcomes.

**Robustness**  
The ability of a treatment system to maintain performance despite changes in source-water quality, flow, or operating conditions.

